76561198006880345,Recommended,278910,15821247,"Posted: 13 May, 2015",all,Beef Supreme,"Interplanetary is an easily overlooked indie game available on steam for around $10.  It is a turn-based strategy game with two phases. The first phase consists of a research and development turn during which players select technologies, build infrastructure, and place buildings on their planet. The second phase consists of players' weapon systems firing, and their trajectory estimates playing out. Each player controls the trajectory of their weapons which are acted upon by the gravity of celestial bodies within the solar system. The time period seems to be set in the near future, and the technology available reflects this appropriately. The single goal of this game is to enact planetary genocide against your rivals.The game feels somewhat like a match of Risk, in space, and with some basic grand-strategy elements, and ballistic physics.  Like Risk, players can expect to spend about one to five hours per game.  And like Risk, the game can get quite addictive, especially considering that it provides online multiplayer as well as local hotseat.  Hotseat allows multiple players to play the same game on the same pc together, and is an extremely underrated feature which is often left out of turn-based strategy games.There are a few things that I believe would add to the game.  For instance, the ability to colonize or conquer planets within the solar system, an “upgrade all” feature for buildings, the ability to name your planets and cities, and basic social, diplomatic, and political policies could add a great level of depth and immersion.Nevertheless, the gameplay is inviting.  Interplantary does not try to be something it is not. It remains simple enough to pick up and quickly get the hang of, short enough to play casually, and immersive enough to allow the imagination some stomping grounds. Overall, this game is definitely worth the asking price, especially if you like to have a few friends over for an afternoon of casual strategy and camaraderie. On sale for under $5, this title would be a steal in a steam-sale splurge."
