76561197986955769,Recommended,278910,19684731,"Posted: 13 December, 2015",all,Bloody Spy!,"AN EXCELLENT ARTILLERY SPACE GAMEI’ve been a fan of artillery games for many many years. I’ve played most of the Worms games and loved them (most of them), and I loved playing a game called Tanks way back in the early 90s. Yes I’m old. I had to break out of the retirement home just to write this review for you guys so please give it a thumbs up.Anyway, Interplanetary differs from all of the other artillery games I’ve played in that the developers have taken the genre into outer space. Boy does it work wonderfully in this new playground! Because planets are continually orbiting their host stars you have to predict where you think the enemy planet will be by the time your projectile will have reached it after having traversed the star system - very much like leading a target with a sniper rifle in a first-person shooter game.Not only do you have to take into account the movement of your target planet as it performs its orbit, you also have to consider the movement of other orbiting bodies, their gravity wells, and the fact that they may move in to the way of your otherwise well-aimed shot. I’ve often been saved from the onslaught of incoming enemy fire by an uninhabited planet “heroically” diving in the way to bear the full brunt of the barrage. Thank you, physics! :DMoreover, you have to take into consideration the rotation of your planet and that of the target planet too. If you’ve built a laser and it’s on the opposite side of your planet facing away from the enemy then it’ll be completely useless for that targeting turn until your planet has rotated to face the correct direction. Likewise, if you’re aiming for a particular enemy city and it’s currently on the opposite side of the planet, from your point of view, then it’ll make it a lot more difficult to hit, and you may even have to wait until the planet’s rotation has put it on the side that’s facing you to score a successful attack.Very basically, in each turn you can build, undertake research, and shoot at your enemies. You have to plan this carefully because firing lots of weapons in one turn may not leave you with any energy remaining to begin contruction projects that round. This is true the other way around: too much building and you'll have no energy left to fire your weapons. So it's best to go on the offensive when you've got easy shots lined up, and build up your planet when the targets are far away and with lots of celestial bodies obstructing the path.You then win the game by destroying all of the enemy's cities and massacring the millions of civilians who, hitherto, inhabited it.PROS- Single player and multiplayer with up to 7 enemies in both cases. This can provide some very interesting and challenging matches, especially when one player's shot misses the intended target and hits someone else instead :D- Buildings and cities are upgradeable e.g. power plants can produce even more energy, satellite arrays have improved detection of enemy structures, HP increase...- Weapons are upgradeable e.g. increased damage, reduced power consumption,- Lots of great upgrades to research and unlock via the tech tree.- Great orchestral soundtrack that adds wonderfully to the atmosphere.- Firing a shot around the sun only to have it slung-shot back in your direction, hit your own planet, and destroy your own buildings is surprisingly good fun. There’s even a Steam achievement if you manage to do that! :DCONS- Relatively few weapons: rain gun, missile, laser, solar laser, asteroid diversion... That’s it, sadly.- The computer AI has pretty much perfect aim. In my experience the AI shots almost never miss.- All of the matches are played in just unary star systems (i.e. just one sun). I know it would make aiming interplanetary projectiles a lot more difficult in binary or ternary solar systems (2 or 3 stars respectively), what with all of the extra gravity wells, but it would be a great challenge for those who want a ‘hardcore’ game mode.- (as an extension of the last point) All of the host stars are just main sequence stars like our Sun. It would have been great to have had different star types like blue super giants and white dwarfs. With their differing sizes (and different mass) firing projectiles through the planetary system would require very different trajectories and velocities with such different stars. Also, their very different masses, and therfore gravity, would greatly affect the angular velocities of the orbiting planets - another factor that would influence how you’d have to plan your trajectory paths during the targeting phase.I’d easily give Interplanetary an 8 or 8.5 out of 10. It would instantly get an extra point if the developer added the “missing content” outlined in my cons section.If you like turn-based strategy games, with excellent artillery action which requires precise planning, and also involves base building with research then Interplanetary should be an insta-buy for you.As always, leave any questions below and I’ll get back to you.Happy mass-murdering!"
